16/10/2008
ATHENS, Greece -- The government on Wednesday (October 15th) pledged up to 28 billion euros to help its banking sector cope with the international financial crisis. 
Presenting a package of measures, Finance Minister George Alogoskoufis said the government would offer a state guarantee worth 15 billion euros to all financial institutions in the country. 
The package also includes issuing special bonds to financial institutions worth up to 8 billion euros, with banks offering adequate collateral. 
The government will also offer up to 5 billion euros to strengthen the banks' capital base. 
The state will purchase banks' preferential stocks. 
Main opposition PASOK leader George Papandreou criticised the plan as an "open cheque" for banks. 
(ANA-MPA, Kathimerini, ERT, AP - 15/10/08)
